Caching in React can happen at multiple layers: component rendering, computed values, API requests, application state, browser storage, and network responses. Different strategies solve different performance problems.

1. Component Memoization (React.memo)

Purpose

Prevents unnecessary re-renders of a component when its props haven't changed.

How it works

Step 1: Parent component renders.

Step 2: React compares current props with previous props.

Step 3: If props are unchanged, React skips rendering the child component.

Step 4: Existing rendered output is reused.

Example

import React from "react";

const UserCard = React.memo(({ name }) => {
  console.log("Rendering UserCard");
  return <div>{name}</div>;
});

export default UserCard;

Use when

Components render frequently.

Props change rarely.

Rendering is expensive.


Benefits

Reduces unnecessary rendering work.

Improves UI responsiveness.



---

2. Function Memoization (useCallback)

Purpose

Caches function references between renders.

Without caching, React creates a new function every render.

How it works

Step 1: Component renders.

Step 2: React stores the callback.

Step 3: On next render, dependencies are checked.

Step 4: If dependencies haven't changed, same function reference is returned.

Example

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  console.log("Clicked");
}, []);

Why important

<Child onClick={handleClick} />

Without useCallback, Child may re-render because onClick gets a new reference every render.

Use when

Passing callbacks to memoized children.

Function creation causes unnecessary updates.



---

3. Value Memoization (useMemo)

Purpose

Caches expensive calculations.

How it works

Step 1: React executes calculation.

Step 2: Stores result.

Step 3: Dependency array is monitored.

Step 4: If dependencies don't change, cached result is returned.

Example

const filteredUsers = useMemo(() => {
  return users.filter(user => user.active);
}, [users]);

Without useMemo

Filtering runs on every render.

With useMemo

Filtering runs only when users changes.

Use when

Sorting large lists.

Data transformations.

Complex calculations.



---

4. API Response Caching with React Query (TanStack Query)

Purpose

Caches server responses automatically.

How it works

Step 1: Component requests data.

const { data } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["users"],
  queryFn: fetchUsers
});

Step 2: Query fetches data from server.

Step 3: Response is stored in cache.

Step 4: Other components requesting the same query receive cached data.

Step 5: Background refetch updates cache when needed.

Cache Lifecycle

Server
   ↓
React Query Fetch
   ↓
Cache Store
   ↓
Multiple Components

Benefits

Automatic caching

Deduplication

Background refresh

Cache invalidation



---

5. SWR Cache Strategy

Purpose

Implements the "Stale While Revalidate" pattern.

Popular library: [SWR](https://swr.vercel.app?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

How it works

Step 1: Check cache.

Step 2: If cached data exists, display immediately.

Step 3: Fetch fresh data in background.

Step 4: Update UI when new data arrives.

Example

const { data } = useSWR(
  "/api/users",
  fetcher
);

Flow

Cached Data
     ↓
Show Immediately
     ↓
Background Fetch
     ↓
Update Cache
     ↓
Re-render UI

Benefit

Users see data instantly while still receiving fresh updates.


---

6. Global State Caching

Purpose

Store data centrally so multiple components reuse it.

Libraries:

[Redux Toolkit](https://redux-toolkit.js.org?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

[Zustand](https://zustand-demo.pmnd.rs?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

React Context


How it works

Step 1: Fetch data once.

Step 2: Store in global state.

Step 3: Components read shared state.

Step 4: Avoid duplicate API calls.

Example

const useUserStore = create((set) => ({
  users: [],
  setUsers: (users) => set({ users })
}));


---

7. Browser Storage Caching

Purpose

Persist data across page reloads.

Options

Storage	Lifetime

localStorage	Permanent
sessionStorage	Browser tab session
IndexedDB	Large datasets


Example

Store

localStorage.setItem(
  "users",
  JSON.stringify(users)
);

Retrieve

const users = JSON.parse(
  localStorage.getItem("users")
);

Flow

API Response
     ↓
localStorage
     ↓
Page Refresh
     ↓
Load Cached Data

Use when

User preferences

Theme settings

Offline support



---

8. Service Worker Caching (PWA)

Purpose

Cache network resources for offline access.

Typically implemented with:

[Workbox](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/workbox?utm_source=chatgpt.com)


How it works

Step 1: User visits site.

Step 2: Service worker installs.

Step 3: Static assets are cached.

Step 4: Future requests are served from cache.

Example Flow

First Visit
    ↓
Cache JS/CSS/Images
    ↓
Next Visit
    ↓
Serve from Cache

Benefits

Faster load times

Offline support

Reduced server traffic



---

9. HTTP Cache

Purpose

Use browser caching via server headers.

Common Headers

Cache-Control: max-age=3600
ETag: "abc123"
Last-Modified: Tue, 16 Jun 2026 10:00:00 GMT

How it works

Step 1: Browser downloads resource.

Step 2: Browser stores it.

Step 3: Next request checks cache validity.

Step 4: Browser reuses cached response if valid.

Types

Strong caching

Conditional caching

CDN caching


Benefits

Faster page loads

Less network traffic



---

10. Lazy Loading + Code Splitting Cache

Purpose

Load JavaScript only when needed and cache downloaded chunks.

Example

const Dashboard = React.lazy(() =>
  import("./Dashboard")
);

How it works

Step 1: Initial bundle loads.

Step 2: User navigates to Dashboard.

Step 3: Chunk downloads.

Step 4: Browser caches chunk.

Step 5: Future visits use cached chunk.

Benefits

Smaller initial bundle

Faster startup

Better caching efficiency



---

Which Strategy Should You Use?

Problem	Recommended Cache Strategy

Expensive calculations	useMemo
Stable function references	useCallback
Prevent child re-renders	React.memo
API data caching	TanStack Query / SWR
Share data across components	Redux / Zustand / Context
Persist data after refresh	localStorage / IndexedDB
Offline support	Service Worker
Static assets	HTTP Cache
Large bundles	Lazy Loading + Code Splitting


Typical Production Setup

A modern React application often combines several caching layers:

HTTP Cache
    ↓
Service Worker Cache
    ↓
React Query Cache
    ↓
Redux/Zustand Store
    ↓
useMemo / useCallback / React.memo

Each layer solves a different bottleneck, giving both faster network performance and faster rendering performance.


These are three important concepts in modern React applications:

1. TanStack Query (React Query) → Server state management and data fetching.


2. Lazy Loading → Loading components/resources only when needed.


3. Code Splitting → Splitting JavaScript bundles into smaller chunks.



They solve different problems but are often used together to improve performance and user experience.


---

1. TanStack Query (React Query)

What Problem Does It Solve?

Without TanStack Query, data fetching often looks like this:

import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

function Users() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users")
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        setUsers(data);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}

Problems:

Manual loading state

Manual error handling

No caching

Duplicate requests

Refetch logic is difficult

Pagination becomes complex


TanStack Query handles all of this.


---

Installation

npm install @tanstack/react-query


---

Setup

Create Query Client

import { QueryClient } from "@tanstack/react-query";

export const queryClient = new QueryClient();

Wrap App

import { QueryClientProvider } from "@tanstack/react-query";
import { queryClient } from "./queryClient";

function App() {
  return (
    <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
      <Users />
    </QueryClientProvider>
  );
}


---

Basic Query Example

API Function

const fetchUsers = async () => {
  const response = await fetch(
    "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users"
  );

  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error("Failed to fetch users");
  }

  return response.json();
};

Component

import { useQuery } from "@tanstack/react-query";

function Users() {
  const {
    data,
    isLoading,
    error
  } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ["users"],
    queryFn: fetchUsers
  });

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error occurred</p>;

  return (
    <ul>
      {data.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}


---

Understanding queryKey

useQuery({
  queryKey: ["users"],
  queryFn: fetchUsers
});

Think of queryKey as a cache identifier.

["users"]

Cache entry:

{
  users: [...]
}

Parameterized query:

useQuery({
  queryKey: ["user", userId],
  queryFn: () => fetchUser(userId)
});

Cache:

["user", 1]
["user", 2]
["user", 3]

Each user gets its own cache.


---

Caching

First request:

Server → Fetch Data

Second request:

Cache → Return Data Instantly

No extra network call until cache expires.

useQuery({
  queryKey: ["users"],
  queryFn: fetchUsers,
  staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5
});

5 minutes cache freshness.


---

Background Refetching

TanStack Query can refresh data automatically.

useQuery({
  queryKey: ["users"],
  queryFn: fetchUsers,
  refetchOnWindowFocus: true
});

User returns to tab:

Tab Focus
    ↓
Background Fetch
    ↓
UI Updated


---

Mutations (POST, PUT, DELETE)

Fetching = Query

Updating = Mutation

Add User

import { useMutation } from "@tanstack/react-query";

const addUser = async (user) => {
  return fetch("/users", {
    method: "POST",
    body: JSON.stringify(user)
  });
};

function AddUser() {
  const mutation = useMutation({
    mutationFn: addUser
  });

  return (
    <button
      onClick={() =>
        mutation.mutate({
          name: "John"
        })
      }
    >
      Add User
    </button>
  );
}


---

Invalidating Queries

After creating a user:

import { useQueryClient } from "@tanstack/react-query";

const queryClient = useQueryClient();

const mutation = useMutation({
  mutationFn: addUser,
  onSuccess: () => {
    queryClient.invalidateQueries({
      queryKey: ["users"]
    });
  }
});

Flow:

Add User
    ↓
Success
    ↓
Invalidate Cache
    ↓
Refetch Users


---

Infinite Query Example

import { useInfiniteQuery } from "@tanstack/react-query";

const fetchPosts = async ({ pageParam = 1 }) => {
  const res = await fetch(`/posts?page=${pageParam}`);
  return res.json();
};

const {
  data,
  fetchNextPage,
  hasNextPage
} = useInfiniteQuery({
  queryKey: ["posts"],
  queryFn: fetchPosts,
  getNextPageParam: (lastPage) => {
    return lastPage.nextPage;
  }
});

Useful for:

Social feeds

Infinite scrolling

Chat applications



