2. Lazy Loading

What is Lazy Loading?

Load resources only when needed.

Instead of loading everything at startup:

App Start
 ├─ Home
 ├─ Dashboard
 ├─ Settings
 ├─ Profile
 └─ Reports

Load only:

App Start
 └─ Home

Others load later.


---

React Lazy

Normal Import

import Dashboard from "./Dashboard";

Loaded immediately.


---

Lazy Import

import React, { lazy } from "react";

const Dashboard = lazy(() =>
  import("./Dashboard")
);

Dashboard is downloaded only when rendered.


---

Suspense

React needs a fallback while downloading.

import { Suspense } from "react";

<Suspense fallback={<p>Loading...</p>}>
  <Dashboard />
</Suspense>


---

Route-Based Lazy Loading

Most common use case.

const Home = lazy(() => import("./Home"));
const Profile = lazy(() => import("./Profile"));
const Settings = lazy(() => import("./Settings"));

<Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
  <Routes>
    <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
    <Route path="/profile" element={<Profile />} />
    <Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
  </Routes>
</Suspense>


---

Before Lazy Loading

main.js
 ├─ Home
 ├─ Profile
 ├─ Settings
 └─ Dashboard

Bundle Size = 1 MB

User downloads everything.


---

After Lazy Loading

main.js = 200 KB

profile.chunk.js = 300 KB
settings.chunk.js = 250 KB
dashboard.chunk.js = 250 KB

Only needed chunks are downloaded.


---

3. Code Splitting

What is Code Splitting?

Breaking one large JavaScript bundle into multiple smaller bundles.

Without code splitting:

bundle.js
 └─ 3 MB

Browser downloads everything.


---

With code splitting:

main.js
home.chunk.js
dashboard.chunk.js
settings.chunk.js

Downloaded on demand.


---

How React Implements It

Code splitting is usually achieved through:

React.lazy()

and

dynamic import()

Example:

const Settings = lazy(() =>
  import("./Settings")
);

Webpack/Vite creates:

settings.chunk.js

automatically.


---

Dynamic Import

import("./Settings")
  .then(module => {
    console.log(module.default);
  });

This tells the bundler:

Create separate chunk


---

Manual Code Splitting Example

Heavy Chart Library

Imagine:

import Chart from "chart.js";

Chart.js adds:

500 KB

Instead:

const ChartPage = lazy(() =>
  import("./ChartPage")
);

Only load chart code when needed.


---

Named Export Example

Component:

export const Settings = () => {
  return <h1>Settings</h1>;
};

Lazy import:

const Settings = lazy(() =>
  import("./Settings").then(module => ({
    default: module.Settings
  }))
);


---

Combining All Three

Real-world dashboard:

Dashboard App
 ├─ Users Page
 ├─ Orders Page
 ├─ Analytics Page
 └─ Settings Page

Lazy Loaded Routes

const Users = lazy(() => import("./Users"));
const Orders = lazy(() => import("./Orders"));
const Analytics = lazy(() => import("./Analytics"));

Each page becomes its own chunk.


